A '''bailleur''', a French term, is a land owner who outsourced uncultivated parcels of land as part of an early [[Middle Age]] sharecropping system known as ''complant'' &mdash; a precursor to the [[métayage]] system. Under this system, a laborer known as a [[prendeur]] would agree to cultivate land owned by the ''bailleur'' in exchange for ownership of the crop and its production. For use of the ''bailleur's'' soil, the ''prendeur'' promised a share (normally a third to two-thirds) of the crop's production or its revenue to the ''bailleur''. The length of this partnership varied and sometimes would extend over generations.<ref>Hugh Johnson, ''Vintage: The Story of Wine'' pg 116. Simon and Schuster 1989</ref> 

